block is symptom not cause\\).;wayne=Wayne maps spec-to-reality. Documentation says documented remedies bypass gates. Observed reality — divineos ask topic piped through head fails bypass on the pipe character. The gap is the readability pattern operator uses constantly. Invariant to preserve — documented remedies bypassable in normal usage shape not just bare-command shape. Fix strip-safe-output-tail preserves the invariant across the readability-tail case.;knuth=Knuth applies precise specification matching. What does the specification say a bypass command IS — a command starting with a documented remedy prefix. What does the current implementation actually check — presence-of-shell-metacharacter anywhere in the command string. Those two specifications diverge on the pipe-tail case. Precise fix — the specification should be a command whose leading segment is a documented remedy and whose remainder is either empty or a known-safe filter chain.;norman=Norman evaluation gulf. Can the user determine what actions are available when the gate blocks — yes, the block message names divineos ask as the remedy. Can the user perform the action — no, because using ask naturally with a pipe fails the bypass. This is a gulf-of-execution failure: the tool the design points at cannot actually be used in its natural shape. What happens when the user makes an error — the block re-fires and the user has no way forward without stripping the pipe or bypassing the gate entirely.' --synthesis 'Seven lenses walked and all converge. Wayne and Knuth both name the spec-to-reality divergence: the bypass specification says '\\\\''documented remedy'\\\\'' but the implementation checks '\\\\''no shell metachars anywhere'\\\\''. Dijkstra and Pearl agree the intervention point is at check B \\(strip safe tail before compound-shape check\\), not at operator behavior. Schneier confirms a closed allow-list of output filters plus args-regex excluding shell metachars closes readability without opening c